Problem Statement: Given an integer array nums, return true if any value appears at least twice in the array, and return false if every element is distinct.
solution->
// Solution class containing the method
class Solution {
    // Function to check for duplicates using sorting
    public boolean containsDuplicate(int[] nums) {
        // Sort the array to bring duplicates together
        Arrays.sort(nums);

        // Compare each element with its previous one
        for (int index = 1; index < nums.length; index++) {
            if (nums[index] == nums[index - 1]) {
                return true; // Duplicate found
            }
        }

        return false; // No duplicates
    }
}

// Main class to run the program
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Sample input array
        int[] nums = {1, 2, 3, 1};

        // Create object of Solution class
        Solution sol = new Solution();

        // Call the function
        boolean res = sol.containsDuplicate(nums);

        // Print result
        System.out.println(res ? "true" : "false");
    }
}

Given an integer array nums, return an array answer such that answer[i] is equal to the product of all the elements of nums except nums[i].

The product of any prefix or suffix of nums is guaranteed to fit in a 32-bit integer.

You must write an algorithm that runs in O(n) time and without using the division operation.

 

Example 1:

Input: nums = [1,2,3,4]
Output: [24,12,8,6]
Example 2:

Input: nums = [-1,1,0,-3,3]
Output: [0,0,9,0,0]

solutio->
class Solution {
    public int[] productExceptSelf(int[] nums) {
      int n = nums.length;
      int[] answer = new int[n];
      answer[0] = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            // answer[i] is the product of nums[0] * nums[1] * ... * nums[i-1]
            answer[i] = answer[i - 1] * nums[i - 1];
        }
         int rightProduct = 1;
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            // For each answer[i], it currently holds the product of elements to its left.
            // We multiply it by the 'rightProduct' (which contains the product of elements
            // to its right for the current iteration) to get the final result.
            answer[i] = answer[i] * rightProduct;

            // Update 'rightProduct' for the next iteration (moving leftwards).
            // It now includes nums[i] for the calculation of the next element to its left.
            rightProduct = rightProduct * nums[i];
        }
         return answer;
  
    }
}
